{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_iris_ver01/data/sn78002169/0027955890A/1946060501/0443.xml":{"full_text":"captain callum\nKILLED IN CRASH\nFormer City Resident Dies\nIn Air Accident\nIn Austria\nCapt. Gaston Ward Callum, 29. of\nWilmington and Greensboro, was\n(tilled in an airplane accident in\nAustralia, May 28, it has been\nlearned from the War Department.\nHe is the son of Mr. and Mrs. Wil\nliam L. Callum, Jr., formerly of\n3805 Princess street, Wilmington,\nCaptain Callum is well known here.\nFighter Pilot\nHe enlisted early in 1942 with\nthe Army Air corps taking training\nts a fighter pilot.\nServing a number of months in\nAfrica and Italy, he piled up a\nrecord of 135 combat missions, be\ning shot down twice in action, both\ntimes without injury.\nCaptain Callum was born in\nAsheville and has resided in\nGreensboro and Wilmington\nattending the University of North\nCarolina where he was a member\nof the wrestling team. Prior to en\ntering the service he had been con\nnected with the General Motors\ncorporation in Charlotte.\nWar Record\nHolder of the Silver Star, the\nDistinguished Flying Cross, the Air\nMedal and a Presidential Unit Cita\ntion. he had only recently received\nhis commission in the regular\nArmy and left this country the\nmiddle of April for Austria where\nhe was stationed with the 79th\nFighter group at Linz on his third\ntour of duty overseas.\nSurviving are his parents, now\nresidents of Baltimore; and two\nbrothers, W. L Callum, III, Char\nlotte, and John Callum, Baltimore.\nSLIGHT MISTAKE\nSTOUGHTON, Wis., June 4\u2014(\u00a3>)\u2014\nThe housing shortage being what\nit is, Tom Jenson was tickled\nwhen construction of his new home\nwas completed. Then he discovered\na slight mistake. The new house\nwas not on his property. Tuesday\nhe completed arrangements for\npurchasing the lot.\nDIAL 2-8675 for\nElectrical Service\nContracting Repairing\nResidential or Commercial\nBrooks Electrical Co.\n312 Southern Bldg.\nTraining Officer I\nAssigned as training officer\nfor the Veterans Administra\ntion, Edward T. Noel, above,\nwill work the three county area\nof New Hanover, Pender, and\nBrunswick counties from the\nVA office in Wilmington\u2019s Tide\nwater building.\u2014STAR STAFF\nPHOTO.\nRaleigh AP Newsman\nAccepts New Post\nRALEIGH, June 4.\u2014UP)\u2014Bloys W.\nBritt, for the last four years at\ntached to the Raleigh bureau of\nthe Associated Press, announced\nTuesday that he would become\nsecretary of the Henderson Cham\nber of Commerce and supervisor\nof tobacco sale here on July 1.\nThe announcement followed a\nmeeting of officials of the two bod\nies. Fred S. Royster is chamber\nof commerce president.\nBritt, a native of Wayne county,\nhas had newspaper experience in\nthe Carolinas and Virginia. For\nthree years he was co-promotor of\nthe Wallace strawberry festival.\nThe common American pocket\ngopher has fur-lined pockets in his\ncheeks.\nFURNACE CLEANING!\nRust and corrosion during the\nsummer months are harmful to\nheating equipment.\nLet us clean your plant NOW with\ncur special heavy duty vacuum\ncleaners.\nSPRINGER COAL OIL CO.\nDial 5261\nFirst Shipment In 5 Years\nLimited Number!\nHeai Flow\nElectric Toasters\nNow you can have golden brown toast with\none of these handsome Electric Toasters.\nCome in and get yours while the supply lasts.\nEASY TERMS.\nGUARANTEED\nFor 1 Year Against Mechanical\nand Structural Failure\nOPEN AN ACCOUNT\nTerms As Low As 1.25 Weekly\nOur Store Will Be Closed\nThis Afternoon And Every Wednesday\nAfternoon Thru June, July and August\nel Bex\nV 109 H. FRONT STRUT\nWilmington\u2019s Largest Credit Jewelers\nWorld-Wide News\nIN BRIEF\nBIDAULT AT TOP\nPARIS, June 4.\u2014(U.PJ\u2014 Foreign\nMinister Georges Bidault, leader\nof the popular Republican party,\nemerged from the first 24 hours of\nhectic political parleys Tuesday as\nthe most likely candidate for prime\nminister of France.\nDEPUTIES CLASH\nPARIS, June 4~<U.R)\u2014The depu\nties of the \u201cBig Four\u201d foreign min\nisters clashed Tuesday over a Rus\nsian demand that Bulgaria be al\nlowed a stronger air force than\nRomania in the post-war settle\nment.\nThe United States, Great Britain\nand France firmly resisted Rus\nsian arguments that Bulgaria\nshould be allowed a larger force\nof combat planes and contended\nthere was no military or political\nreason for favoring Bulgaria over\nRomania.\nSAVOY IN DOUBT\nROME, June 4\u2014(U.PJ\u2014The fate of\nKing Humbert and the ancient\nhouse of Savoy remained in doubt\nTuesday night more than 30 hours\nafter the close of polls in the two\nday referendum on the question\nof monarchy or republic. Latest\nreturns showed a five-to-four vote\nfor a republic but Humbert was\nrunning strong in the traditionally\nroyalist South.\nGARRISON UNDER FIRE\nPARIS, June 4\u2014(U.R)\u2014A govern\nment spokesman said Tuesday\nnight that a French garrison in\nnorthern Indo-China had been un\nder fire from Siamese forces for\nmore than 43 hours.\nBYRNES TO PARIS\nWASHINGTON, June 4 \u2014(U.R)\u2014\nSecretary of State James F. Byrnes\nwill leave for Paris next week\nmore determined than ever to in\nclude an Austrian peace treaty on\nthe agenda of the foreign minis\nters council.\nTINY BABY DIES\nNASHVILLE, Tenn., June 4\u2014(U.R)\n\u2014A tiny baby girl, weighing but\none pound and six ounces and only\nseven inches long, lost her 100-to\none chance for life Tuesday.\nThe baby, born four months pre\nmaturely, died in a hosptal incu\nbator four days after birth.\nPhysicians said the birth of\nsuch a small child was not unusual,\nbut they believed the smallest baby\nto live to maturity weighed one\npound and ten ounces at birth.\nNEW ORLEANS FORGETS\nNEW ORLEANS, June 4.\u2014(U.R)\u2014\nArmed with a Confederate flag,\nReporter Flannery Lewis of the\nNew Orleans Item trooped all over\ntown on Jefferson Davis\u2019 birthday,\nasking if anyone recognized the\nhistoric piece of silk. He asked a\none-legged man, dozens of south\nerners and northerners, too. Fin\nally he approached M'.ss Ethelmae\nRogers, of Omaha, Neb. She not\nonly knew the flag, but named the\nstates its seven stars represented.\nCoal Prices To Rise\nWASHINGTON, June 4r-(/P)\u2014An\nOPA official reported Tuesday\nthat 35 cents a ton is the average\namount of the soft coal price in\ncrease now under consideration.\nThis figure would be based on the\ncosts involved in operating the\nmines six days a week. The official\nsaid the OPA and the Office of\nEconomic Stabilization have been\ninformed unofficially that the gov\nernment plans six-day operation\nfor the present.\nReds Want Own Way\nLONDON, June 4\u2014(U.R)\u2014Russia\nbelieves that its security can be\nmaintained only if every other\ncountry adopts the Soviet system,\nForeign Secretary Ernest Bevin\ncharged Tuesday in the House of\nCommons. This belief, he said, is\na great handicap to Russia and a\ngreat obstacle to peace.\nAzores Base Returned\nWASHINGTON, June 4\u2014(JP)\u2014The\nUnited States has turned back to\nPortugal control of the strategic\nAzores Island Air base developed\nduring the war, while retaining the\nright to use it for 18 months for\nmilitary purposes, Secretary of\nState Byrnes disclosed Tuesday.\nPETRILLO PLEADS\nST. PETERSBURG, Fla. June 4.\n\u2014(U.R)\u2014James Caesar Petrillo\u2019s plea\nto all branches of labor to \u201cget\ntogether and protect ourselves\u201d\nwas being written into resolutions\nTuesday night by the executive\nboard of his American Federation\nof Musicians. The resolutions will\nprobably be made public at the\nWednesday morning session of the\nAFM convention here. They are ex\npected to embody Petrillo\u2019s out\nBowel Cleaning Power\nOf Inner-Aid Medicine\nOne man recently took INNER\nAID three days and sail after\nward that he never would have\nbelieved his body contained so\nmuch filthy substance. He says his\nstomach, intestines, bowels and\nwhole system were so thoroughly\ncleansed that his constant head\naches came to an end, several pim\nply skin eruptions on his face dried\nup overnight, and even the rheu\nmatic pains in his knee disappear\ned. At present he is an altogehter\ndifferent man, feeling fine in every\nway.\nINNER-AID contains 12 Great\nHerbs; they cleanse bowels, clear\ngas from stomach, act on sluggish\nliver and kidneys. Miserable peo\nple soon feel different all over. So\ndon\u2019t go on suffering! Get INNER\nAID. Sold by all drug stores here\nin Wilmington.\nspoken denunciation of the newly\npassed Lea bill the so-called\nanti-Petrillo bill and of pending\nlegislation which he also branded\nas anti-labor.\nFRANCO DANGEROUS?\nNEW YORK, June 4. \u2014<U.R)\u2014'The\nUnited Nations cannot hope for \u201ca\nreally effective system of interna\ntional control of atomic energy\u201d\nso long as the Franco regime re\nmains in power in Spain, a UN\nSecurity Council subcommittee\nwarned Tuesday.\nUnless Franco is ousted and a\nfree Spanish government admitted\nto the UN, the subcommittee de\nclared, there will be a serious\ngap in the UN\u2019s projected world\nsecurity system.\nPAC TEST\nMONTGOMERY, Ala., June 5.\n\u2014(U.R)\u2014 The CIO Political Action\ncommittee faced another test at\nthe polls Tuesday night as Alabama\nvoters balloted at a runoff primary\nfor a governor and a congress\nman. A record turnout of 400,000\nvoters was predicted. Candidates\nfor Governor were Lieut. Gov.\nHandy Ellis, 65-year-old Columbia\nlawyer and veteran of 25 years in\nAlabama politics, and James E.\n(Big Jim) Folsom, 35, who wears\nsize 15 1-2 shoes and the endorse\nment of the PAC.\nPERON INAUGURATED\nBUENOS AIRES, June 4.\u2014ffl\u2014\nJuan Domingo Peron was inaugu\nrated Tuesday as Argentina\u2019s 29th\npresident and pledged himself to a\nbasic international policy of\n\u201cstrong, uncompromising defense\nof our sovereignty and the sincere\nfulfillment of our international\nobligations.\u201d\nCAROLINA TIMBER BOUGHT\nPHILADELPHIA, June 4.\u2014(A5)\u2014\nPhilco Corporation has overcome\nthe critical shortage of cabinet\nwoods for radio receivers to a\ngreat extent by acquiring approxi\nmately 22,000 acres of standing\ntimber in North and South Caro\nlina, John Ballantyne, president,\nannounced Tuesday. Adjacent log\nging and sawmill facilities have\nbeen established and operations\nare now underway, Ballantyne\nsaid.\nLONG MEAT SHORTAGE\nCHICAGO, June 4. Live\nstock men were undecided Tues\nday how effective the governmeat\u2019s\nnew 85 percent slaughter quotas\nwould be in relieving illegal opera\ntions in meat, but they were un\nanimous in predicting shortages of\nthe food product would continue\nfor many months.\nGERMANY GETS GRAIN\nSTUTTGART, Germany June 4\n(yF) American shipments of\nbread gTains to Germany totalled\n95,000 tons in the last half of May,\nLieut Gen. Lucius D. Clay told\nminister-presidents of the U. S.\noccupation zone Tuesday.\nCONFEREES PROGRESS\nNEW YORK, June 4 \u2014(yP)\u2014\"De\nfinite progress\u2019\u201d was made at\nTuesday\u2019s negotiation session be\ntween John L. Lewis\u2019 AFL United\nMine Workers and anthracite op\nerators, both sides said in a state,\nment released afterward. The state_\nment indicated their policy\ngoverning scale committees were\nundertaking the task of forging a\nnew contract for the 75,000 hard\ncoal miners now idle in Pennsyl\nvania.\nMISS WALLACE\u2019S SPECIALTY\nKANSAS CITY, June 4 (A>)\nForty years ago Tuesday Miss\nBessie Wallace was listed as win\nner in the shotput event at the\nannual field day at the Barstow\nschool, a girl\u2019s school where she\nwas taking post-graduate work.\nThen 21 years old, the present Mrs.\nHarry S. Truman excelled at all\nsports, especially tennis and riflng,\naccording to the school\u2019s year\nbook. The field day is still a fea\nture of the school\u2019s closing days.\nBut the shotput event is omitted.\nStassen Says Labor\nLaw Is Totalitarian\nATLANTIC CITY, N. J., June 4.\n\u2014(A1)\u2014Harold E. Stassen, former\ngovernor of Minnesota and men\ntioned as a possible candidate for\nthe Republican presidential nomi\nnation in 1948, declared Tuesday\nthat President Truman\u2019s proposed\nemergency labor legislation was\n\u201ctotalitarian\u201d and would permit\nthe governor to \u201cbreak and de\nstroy\u2019\u2019 any business or union.\nStassen said in an address pre\npared for the 37th annual Rotary\nInternational convention that the\nPresident\u2019 labor legilation \u201cin\nvolves very fundamentally the\nfuture liberties of men, of busi\nness, and of labor, and the future\nwelfare of the people as a whole.\u201d\nHe outlined seven points which\nhe said would correct industrial\ndiscord and adjust the nation\u2019s\neconomy.\nCHARGE DISMISSED\nMURRAY, Ky., June 4\u2014(A>)\u2014A\nmurder charge against Leonard\nManning, 16, in connection with\nthe fatal shooting of his father,\nGervis Manning, last April 10,\nwas dismissed by juvenile judge\nPink Curd Monday. The youth\ntestified he killed his father when\nhe came to remove furnishings\nfrom the rural home the boy said\nhe had maintained for two sisters\nand a brother younger than he,\nafter their parents left them.\nJOB PLACEMENTS\nINCREASING HERE\nHinkle Predicts Unemploy\nment Decline For Im\nmediate Future\nFigures released Tuesday by the\nlocal United States Employment\nService showed a \u201cmarked in\ncrease\u201d in Wilmington employment\nduring May, with 818 persons\ngaining jobs through USES ac\ntion.\nThe May placement record show\ned a 11 3-4 per cent hike over\nApril\u2019s tally; proof according to\nOffice Manager H. M. Hinkle,\n\u201cthat unemployment will be on the\ndecline during the next several\nweeks.\u201d\nThe release revealed that 454 of\nthe May placements were in non\nagricultural occupations.\nApplicants Increase\nApplicants for employment and\nunemployment Benefits during the\nmonth reached a total of 989, it\nwas shown, which is an increase of\n19 per cent over last month.\nIn the same instance total con\ntracts with office increased 37 1-2\nper cent to 18,512 for the May\nperiod.\nJob-Openings\nCurrently there are 321 job-open\nings on file with over one-half re\nquiring skilled labor which the\noffice is unable to furnish.\nOnly nine per cent of the re\ngistrants are women, whereas 60\nper cent of the job openings are\nfor women, the figures disclosed.\nPotential Jobs\nSummarizing the figures, Hinkle\nsaid that approximately 2,300 po\ntential jobs are in sight for area\nworkers within the next several\nweeks.\nHis predictions were based on a\ned into the Brunswick River layup\npossible 500 workers being absorb\nbasin project; 800 by the Regal\nPaper company at Bolton and 500\nwomen workers by local textile\nplants by July 1.\nCOL A. H. HARRISS\nOPERATED ON FOR\nCHEST AILMENT\nColonel Andrew H. Harriss, Jr,,\nson of Dr. and Mrs. Andrew H.\nHarris, 609 Dock Street, underwent\na serious chest operation at Waller\nReed General Hospital, Army\nMedical Center, Washington, D.\nC., yesterday.\nMrs. Harriss, formerly Miss\nLouise Ogden Wright of Washing\nton, D. C. is temporarily residing\nwith her parents at 9606 Riley\nPlace, Silver Spring, Maryland.\nColonel and Mrs. Harriss will\nreturn to Wilmington upon his\nseparation from service following\nthe operation.\nBunn Level Farmer\nHeld In Shooting\nDUNN, June 4.\u2014 m \u2014Hunter\nBethea, Bunn level farmer, was\nheld In the Harnett county jail\nTuesday without bond in connec\ntion with the slaying of his bro\nther-in-law, James Henry Moore,\n31, according to Deputy Sheriff\nKen Matthews, who made the ar\nrest shortly after Moore was shot\nSunday.\nMoore, a farm neighbor of\nBiethea, died in a Fayetteville hos\npital yesterday of a .45 calibre bul\nlet wound.\nI\nArmy Predicts 1,000\nMile Plane Speeding\nDAYTON, O., June 4.\u2014OP)\u2014Fu\nture speeds of 1,000 miles an hour\nfor military jet planes were pre\ndicted by Army Air forces officials\nat Wright Field Tuesday in lifting\nwraps from the Army\u2019s newest\nfighter.\nLatest AAF sky king is the Re\npublic XR-84 Thunderjet, credited\nlike the Lockheed P-80 Shooting\nStar which already is in actual\nservice with a speed at least ap\nproaching 600 miles an hour.\nDial 2-3311 for Newspaper Service\nSTOP\nthat awful\nPRICKLE\nthis fast new wayl\nYou get faster relief-thanks to\nJohnson\u2019s Prickly Heat Powder\nwith bentonite! This super-ab\nsorbent ingredient keeps skin\nreally dry after it\u2019s been soothed\ncooled relieved; lets that\nitchy rash heal in a hurry! It\u2019s\nexclusive in Johnson\u2019s Prickly\nHeat Powder. _\nIIM II I II I I I I I I [I -L.V'' \"\u2014I\nrjfer7NiT\u00a9ulARANteeo by\nM jOHNSO* ba6Y 1,\nJOHNSON\u2019S\nPRICKLY HEAT\nPOWDER\n^ofmnrnJ^ofimcn [\u00a3^rj'\n\u201cMAKE IT fl MILLION!\u201d\nMAKE A CAREER OF AVIATION!\nThe finest training with the latest\nequipment in the field of aviation\nis yours in the U. S. Army Air\nForces. Good pay while you learn.\nOver three-quarters of a million\nhave already joined the new Reg\nular Army. MAKE IT A MILLION!\nGet full facts at your nearest\nArmy Camp or Post, or U. S. Army\nRecruiting Station.\n0. S. ARMY RECRUITING STATION\nRoom 203, P. O. Bldg. Wilmington, N. C. Dial 2-8368\nOr\u2014Recruiting Representative In Post Offices, 10 a.m. to 2 p.m.\nWhiteville\u2014Mondays; Wallace\u2014Wednesdays; Southport\u2014Tuesdays;\nJacksonville\u2014Thursdays\nPOUNDED 1840\nPARK TILFORD\nRESERVE\n\u2022\u2019AHJUTILFOH*\nVReserve;\nV\u2014 4KL\nWN]\u00a7kEY\n^_A BLIMP_^\nmm ft mm usnuEtt, nr., n\u00bb run n% ham nrareu wan aim\nSoviet Union Names\nNew Army Marshals\nBERLIN, June 4.\u2014OP)\u2014General\nVasiili D. Sokolovsky, Soviet com\nmander and military governor in\nGermany, has been promoted to\nmarshal of the Soviet Union, it was\nannounced Tuesday.\nSokolovsky was appointed to his\npresent post in April, succeeding\nMarshal Georgi Zhukov, whom he\nhad previously served as chief of\nstaff. (The Moscow radio, heard\nin London by the Soviet Monitor,\nalso announced that the rank of\nmarshal of aviation has been con\nferred on Colonel General of Avia\ntion Konstantin A. Vershinin.)\nDial 2-3311 For Newspaper Service\nLOOK! THIS LARGE\nSIZE JAR of MOROLIHE\nPetroleum Jelly\nfor minor burns- -cuts, bruis\nes, chafes, abrasions, and\nskin irritations. AidsheaUng.\nand only 10* J\nSTORE CLOSES 1P. M. WEDNESDAYS\nWEDNESDAY MORNING\nI I\nActual Values To $29.98\n\ncJCimit: One to a Customer\n100 Spring and Early Summer Dresses,\nfrom Regular Slock!\nALL PURE SILK\nSHANTUNGS\nGABARDINES\nRAYON JERSEYS\nCREPES AND SHEERS\nLIGHT WEIGHT WOOL JERSEY\nCOOL COTTONS\nONE AND TWO-PIECERS\nPASTELS AND SOLIDS\nSTRIPES, POLKA DOTS AND\nPRINTS\nJUNE; Month of Special Events!\nShop\nEarly!\n214 N. FRONT ST.","height":"26760","width":"20184"}}
